    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-11-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-11-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="262"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <head>262. National Security Decision Memorandum 34<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d262fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 593, Country Files—Middle East, Greece, Vol. I
                        Jan 69–Oct 70. Secret; Nodis. Copies were also sent to the Directors of
                        Central Intelligence and the Bureau of the Budget and to the Chairman of the
                        Joint Chiefs of Staff. This version replaced a November 11 memorandum on the
                        same subject that was rescinded by the White House.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1969-11-14">November 14, 1969</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> Policy Toward Greece—Military
                        Assistance</item>
                </list>
                <p>With reference to the memorandum of September 26, 1969, from the Chairman <gloss
                        target="#t_NSCIG1">NSCIG</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss> to the
                    Chairman, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Review Group entitled “<gloss
                        target="#t_US1">US</gloss> Policy Toward Greece: Military
                    Assistance—Response to <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 52,” and the
                    memorandum of the Secretary of State on this subject dated October 30,
                        1969,<note n="2" xml:id="d262fn2">The report and its conclusions are
                        summarized in <ref target="#d261">Document 261</ref>, to which the
                        memorandum of September 26 was attached (see <ref target="#d257fn4">footnote
                            4, Document 257</ref>). Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP1"
                            >Rogers</persName>ʼs memorandum is <ref target="#d260">Document
                            260</ref>.</note> the President has instructed that: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TH1">Tasca</persName> tell Prime
                            Minister <persName corresp="#p_PLCG1">Papadopoulos</persName> that he is
                            prepared to resume normal military aid shipments, including all items
                            which have been suspended.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TH1">Tasca</persName> make clear that
                            movement toward a constitutional situation would ease <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">US</gloss> problems in speeding the release of the
                            suspended equipment. [This linkage is conceived as a means of improving
                            the atmosphere for removing the suspension of military shipments.]<note
                                n="3" xml:id="d262fn3">Brackets in the original.</note>
                        </item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>The <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> Government, after the President
                            has reviewed Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TH1">Tasca</persName>ʼs
                            report of the Greek Governmentʼs response, begin shipping the suspended
                            items gradually, beginning with the less dramatic items.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>After the Presidentʼs final review and approval, the following public
                            line be taken with members of the Congress and press as necessary:
                            Overriding <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> security interests were the
                            principal factor in the decision to lift the suspension. The <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">US</gloss> Government will continue urging the
                            government to move toward a constitutional situation.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TH1">Tasca</persName> attempt to
                            develop a relationship with Greek government leaders that would permit
                            him to exercise influence for <pb facs="0717" n="673" xml:id="pg_673"/>
                            democratic reform and a relationship with civilian political leaders
                            that would maintain a bridge to possible future governments.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>The Under Secretaries Committee assure the coordinated execution of
                            this policy.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
